{"type":"result","id":"n02-code","category":"negative","prompt":"Write a Python function that reverses a singly linked list.","expect":[],"goldArgs":{},"actual":null,"bailOut":null,"rawText":"The task you've given is about writing a Python function to reverse a singly linked list, which is a programming problem and not related to any of the available macros. Since there's no suitable macro for this request, I'll provide you with an explanation in plain text instead.\n\nTo reverse a singly linked list in Python, you can use three pointers: `prev`, `current`, and `next`. Here’s a simple implementation:\n\n```python\nclass ListNode:\n    def __init__(self, value=0, next=None):\n        self.value = value\n        self.next = next\n\ndef reverse_linked_list(head):\n    prev = None\n    current = head\n    while current is not None:\n        next_node = current.next  # Store the next node\n        current.next = prev       # Reverse the link\n        prev = current            # Move pointers one position ahead\n        current = next_node\n    return prev                   # New head of the reversed list\n\n# Example usage:\n# Creating a linked list: 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> None\nnode1 = ListNode(1)\nnode2 = ListNode(2)\nnode3 = ListNode(3)\nnode1.next = node2\nnode2.next = node3\n\nreversed_head = reverse_linked_list(node1)\n```\n\nThis function takes the head of a singly linked list and returns the new head after reversing it.","latencyMs":13946,"routingCorrect":true,"argKeys":[],"argsScored":false,"argsExact":false}
